First interim analysis for SII Study 3

Introduction

Research on person perception has revealed that people tend to attribute other’s behavior to stable person characteristics, even if it can just as well be explained by reasons such as situational factors or mental states. This tendency is known as the correspondence bias (Gilbert & Malone, 1995) and may play an important role in the domain of political polarization. Specifically, people may attribute each other’s politically relevant behaviors to stable ideological dispositions (such as leftist, conservative, racist, or feminist), while neglecting potential other causes and thereby impeding mutual understanding. To investigate the role of the correspondence bias in political polarization, we examine whether spontaneous ideological inferences are reduced when behaviors are accompanied by information on relatively sufficient reasons for the behavior. We thus extend previous research on spontaneous trait inferences (STI, Winter & Uleman, 1984) and the correspondence bias to spontaneous inferences of ideological dispositions.

Sample Characteristics

For the first interim analysis we collected data from a total of N = XXX participants. Following our pre-registered exclusion criteria, we excluded X participants who did not give informed consent, X who gave the same response in all of the 36 test trials, and X who rated their own data to be unfit for analysis. This resulted in a sample of N = 129 participants (76 female, 49 male, 4 other, 0 not specified; average age M = 28.1 years, SD = 8.3, ranging from 18 to 59). Participants were recruited via the online platform Prolific (www.prolific.co) and received monetary compensation of 3.00 GBP for completing the 20-minute study. An additional X people started the experiment on prolific but either returned their submission, timed-out, or only partially completed the experiment due to technical issues.

On average, participants reported to be rather left leaning (M = 3.6, SD = 1.4 on a scale from 1 = left to 10 = right) and rather interested in politics (M = 6.2, SD = 1.9, on a scale ranging from 1 = not at all to 10 = very strongly).

Manipulation check

man_check <- d_long %>%
    select(subject_id, reason_type, sufficiency) %>%
    group_by(subject_id, reason_type) %>%
    summarize(mn_sufficiency = mean(sufficiency, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
    ungroup() %>%
    pivot_wider(names_from = "reason_type", values_from = "mn_sufficiency") %>%
    mutate(diff = sufficient - control)

# Descriptives
m_suff <- format(round(mean(man_check$sufficient), 2), nsmall = 2)
m_ctrl <- format(round(mean(man_check$control), 2), nsmall = 2)
sd_suff <- format(round(sd(man_check$sufficient), 2), nsmall = 2)
sd_ctrl <- format(round(sd(man_check$control), 2), nsmall = 2)
# One-sided paired t-test
t1 <- t.test(man_check$sufficient, man_check$control,
             paired = TRUE, alternative = "greater")
# P-value in apa format
t1_p <- ifelse(t1$p.value < 0.001, "p < .001",
               paste("p =", sub("0.", ".", round(t1$p.value, 3))))
# Calculating d_z as mean difference divided by sd of the differences
d_z <- format(round(mean(man_check$sufficient - man_check$control) /
                    sd(man_check$sufficient - man_check$control), 2),
              nsmall = 2)

We included a manipulation check for reason type. The sufficient reasons are supposed to sufficiently explain the behaviors, whereas the control reasons are supposed to insufficiently explain the behavior (or not explain the behavior at all). We thus asked participants at the end of the study to rate the sufficiency of each reason for the respective behavior and expected the sufficient reasons to score higher in their sufficiency ratings than the control reasons. To test this, we conducted a paired t-test. On average, participants gave significantly higher sufficiency ratings in the sufficient condition (M = 3.29, SD = 0.61) than in the control condition (M = 2.23, SD = 0.59), t(128) = 17.32, p < .001, dz = 1.52. We infer from this, that our manipulation of reason type worked.

Preregistered hypothesis

# Prepare data
er <- d_long %>%
    select(subject_id, probe_type, reason_type, is_correct, stimulus_set) %>%
    group_by(subject_id, probe_type, reason_type, stimulus_set) %>%
    summarize(fr_n = sum(is_correct == 0), n_trials = n()) %>%
    mutate(fr_rate = fr_n / n_trials) %>%
    select(-fr_n) %>%
    # Find extreme outliers
    ungroup(subject_id) %>%
    mutate(is_extreme = is_extreme(fr_rate)) %>%
    ungroup() %>%
    # Find participants with extreme values in the false
    # recognition rate in at least one experimental condition
    group_by(subject_id) %>%
    mutate(has_extremes = ifelse(TRUE %in% is_extreme, TRUE, FALSE)) %>%
    ungroup()
er_ex <- filter(er, has_extremes == FALSE)

# Anova
er_m1 <- anova_test(
    data = er,
    dv = fr_rate, wid = subject_id, effect.size = "pes",
    within = c(probe_type, reason_type)
)
er_m2 <- anova_test(
    data = er,
    dv = fr_rate, wid = subject_id, effect.size = "pes",
    within = c(probe_type, reason_type), between = stimulus_set
)

We looked for extreme outliers in each cell of the design. We defined them as values above Q3 + 3 * IQR or below Q1 - 3 * IQR. We found and excluded 0 extreme outliers. Upon visual inspection the distributions of error rates in all experimental conditions did not seem severely non-normal. Therefore, a two-way repeated-measures ANOVA was performed to evaluate the effect of probe type and reason type on the false recognition rates.

The main effect for probe type was significant, F(1, 128) = 66.035, p < .001, \(\eta_{p}^{2}\) = .34. There was no significant interaction between probe type and reason type, F(1, 128) = 3.333, p = .07, \(\eta_{p}^{2}\) = .025.

Exploratory reaction time analysis

rt <- d_long %>%
    mutate(across(starts_with("rt_"), ~ifelse(is_correct == 0, NA, .))) %>%
    select(subject_id, probe_type, reason_type, starts_with("rt_")) %>%
    group_by(subject_id, probe_type, reason_type) %>%
    summarize(across(everything(), mean, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
    # Find extreme outliers and missing values in rt_M2SD_log
    ungroup(subject_id) %>%
    mutate(
        is_extreme = is_extreme(rt_M2SD_log),
        is_missing = is.na(rt_M2SD_log)) %>%
    ungroup() %>%
    # Find participants with missing or extreme values in
    # rt_M2SD_log in at least one experimental condition
    group_by(subject_id) %>%
    mutate(
        has_missings = ifelse(TRUE %in% is_missing, TRUE, FALSE),
        has_extremes = ifelse(TRUE %in% is_extreme, TRUE, FALSE)) %>%
    ungroup()
rt_ex <- rt %>%
    filter(has_missings == FALSE) %>%
    filter(has_extremes == FALSE)
# Anova
rt_m1 <- anova_test(
    data = rt_ex,
    dv = rt_M2SD_log, wid = subject_id, effect.size = "pes",
    within = c(probe_type, reason_type)
)

To prepare the response latency data for the analysis we applied an individual cut-off of each participant’s mean plus two standard deviations for slow responses and the log-transformation and then computed the average for each experimental condition. We looked for extreme outliers in each cell of the design. We defined them as values above Q3 + 3 * IQR or below Q1 - 3 * IQR. We found and excluded NA extreme outliers. Upon visual inspection the distributions in the different conditions did not seem severely non-normal. We therefore did not apply further transformations. A two-way repeated-measures ANOVA was performed to evaluate the effect of probe type and reason type on the mean response latencies.

The main effect for probe type was significant, F(1, 123) = 2.426, p = .122, \(\eta_{p}^{2}\) = .019. There was no significant interaction between probe type and reason type, F(1, 123) = 2.199, p = .141, \(\eta_{p}^{2}\) = .018.

Multiverse analysis

Because there are no conventions regarding outlier correction and transformations, we follow a recommendation by Krieglmeyer & Deutsch (2010) and employ a multiverse analysis using different cut-off criteria (no cut-off, 8000 ms, 6000 ms, and 4000 ms) and transformations (no transformation, a log-transformation, and an inverse transformation) and report each combination’s effects on the results.

rt_multi <- d_long %>%
    mutate(across(starts_with("rt_"), ~ifelse(is_correct == 0, NA, .))) %>%
    select(subject_id, probe_type, reason_type, starts_with("rt_")) %>%
    group_by(subject_id, probe_type, reason_type) %>%
    summarize(across(everything(), mean, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
    ungroup() %>%
    pivot_longer(
        cols = starts_with("rt"),
        names_to = c(NA, "cutoff", "trans"),
        values_to = "rt",
        names_sep = "_")

# Loop over all combinations of cutoffs and transformations
multi <- multi_h1 <- multi_h2 <- data.frame(
    cutoff = rep(c("none", "M2SD", "f80", "f60", "f40"), 3),
    transformation = c(rep("none", 5), rep("log", 5), rep("inv", 5)))
for (c in seq(nrow(multi))) {
    rt_multi_c <- rt_multi %>%
        # Filter data using c-th cutoff and transformation
        filter(cutoff == multi$cutoff[c] & trans == multi$transformation[c]) %>%
        # Find extreme outliers and missing values in rt_M2SD_log
        group_by(probe_type, reason_type) %>%
        mutate(is_extreme = is_extreme(rt), is_missing = is.na(rt)) %>%
        ungroup() %>%
        # Exclude participants with missing or extreme values in
        # rt_M2SD_log in at least one experimental condition
        group_by(subject_id) %>%
        mutate(
            has_missings = ifelse(TRUE %in% is_missing, TRUE, FALSE),
            has_extremes = ifelse(TRUE %in% is_extreme, TRUE, FALSE)) %>%
        ungroup() %>%
        filter(has_missings == FALSE & has_extremes == FALSE)

    # Calculate test and effect size
    mv1 <- anova_test(
        data = rt_multi_c,
        dv = rt, wid = subject_id, effect.size = "pes",
        within = c(probe_type, reason_type)
    )
    # Save test statistics for h1
    multi_h1$DFn[c] <- mv1$DFn[1]
    multi_h1$DFd[c] <- mv1$DFc[1]
    multi_h1$F[c] <- mv1$F[1]
    multi_h1$p[c] <- format_p(mv1$p[1], num_only = TRUE)
    multi_h1$pes[c] <- format_apa(mv1$pes[1], leading_zero = FALSE)

    # Save test statistics for h2
    multi_h2$DFn[c] <- mv1$DFn[3]
    multi_h2$DFd[c] <- mv1$DFc[3]
    multi_h2$F[c] <- mv1$F[3]
    multi_h2$p[c] <- format_p(mv1$p[3], num_only = TRUE)
    multi_h2$pes[c] <- format_apa(mv1$pes[3], leading_zero = FALSE)
}

Exploratory by-item analysis

# Calculate discounting effect for each item and predict by sufficiency
sufficiency <- d_long %>%
    select(item_id, reason_type, sufficiency) %>%
    group_by(item_id, reason_type) %>%
    summarize(
        suff_sd = sd(sufficiency, na.rm = TRUE),
        suff_mn = mean(sufficiency, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
    ungroup()

by_item <- d_long %>%
    select(item_id, behavior, probe_type, reason_type, is_correct) %>%
    mutate(probe_type = recode(probe_type, "implied" = "im", "implied other" = "io")) %>% # nolint
    group_by(item_id, behavior, probe_type, reason_type) %>%
    summarize(fr_n = sum(is_correct == 0), n_trials = n()) %>%
    ungroup() %>%
    mutate(fr_rate = fr_n / n_trials) %>%
    select(-fr_n) %>%
    pivot_wider(names_from = probe_type, values_from = c(fr_rate, n_trials)) %>%
    left_join(sufficiency) %>%
    mutate(fr_diff = fr_rate_im - fr_rate_io) %>%
    select(-starts_with("n_trials"), -suff_sd)
by_item_disc <- by_item %>%
    select(-fr_rate_im, -fr_rate_io) %>%
    pivot_wider(names_from = reason_type, values_from = c(fr_diff, suff_mn)) %>%
    mutate(
        disc = fr_diff_sufficient - fr_diff_control,
        suff_diff = suff_mn_sufficient - suff_mn_control)

c1 <- cor.test(by_item$fr_diff, by_item$suff_mn)
c1_p <- ifelse(c1$p.value < 0.001, "p < .001",
               paste("p =", sub("0.", ".", round(c1$p.value, 3))))

We conducted exploratory by-item analyses. We calculated average SII-effects for each item * reason type (by substracting the false recognition rate in the implied other condition from the one in the implied condition), with more positive values indicating stronger inference effects. The SII-effect was not significantly correlated with the sufficiency of the reason, r(46) = -1.61, p = .114. However, the direction of the relationship was as expected, with higher sufficiency scores predicting smaller SII-effects.

Exploratory multilevel analysis

# By using multilevel models
d_mlm <- d_long %>%
    select(
        subject_id, item_id, probe_type, reason_type, is_correct,
        sufficiency, gender, age, pol_orientation, pol_interest) %>%
    mutate(
        is_error = abs(1 - is_correct),
        gender = ifelse(gender %in% c("other", "not specified"), NA, gender),
        # Grand mean center level 2 predictors
        age = age - mean(age),
        pol_orientation = pol_orientation - mean(pol_orientation),
        pol_interest = pol_interest - mean(pol_interest),
        probe_type = relevel(probe_type, ref = "implied other")
    ) %>%
    group_by(subject_id) %>%
    mutate(
        sufficiency = sufficiency - mean(sufficiency),
        response = factor(ifelse(
            is_error == TRUE,
            "false recognitions",
            "correct rejections"))) %>%
    mutate(response = factor(response, levels = rev(levels(response)))) %>%
    ungroup()

# Item ID as random effect

    labs(y = "Probability of false recognition", x = "Sufficiency", color = "Response") +

    stat_smooth(

        slab_type = "pdf", scale = 0.15, size = 0.5) +
    scale_color_viridis_d(option = "mako", begin = 0.4, end = 0.85) +
    theme_cs_talk()
